{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"42c9da03-9696-4cf6-bb67-aa00dc2b4aba","content":"The project doesn't exist yet in this workspace, but here's how to configure `mcp.json` for a C# MCP server using **stdio** transport:\n\nCreate `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace root:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- **`command` / `args`** — Uses `dotnet run` to build and launch your project.\n- If you publish a self-contained binary instead, point `command` directly at the executable.\n- Your C# server must use the **stdio transport** (not HTTP/SSE). If you're using the `ModelContextProtocol` NuGet package, call `.WithStdioServerTransport()` in your host builder.\n\n**For a published executable:**\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"src/MyMcpServer/bin/Release/net8.0/MyMcpServer\"\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\nAfter saving, VS Code will prompt you to start the server. You can also run **\"MCP: List Servers\"** from the command palette to verify it's detected.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"fca50dc1-5447-4e1d-8ea7-a2f15900e963","outputTokens":376,"requestId":"7FC5:7D36C:61AEFE9:6AA2D3E:69F15AFC"},"id":"aa5d7afd-65d0-4b87-a0b8-e52331f7e458","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:12:37.937Z","parentId":"bfcbbe57-da56-4bf4-a17e-eee89dac59d8"}
